title: For Sale/Trade:  Beretta 92G Brigadier Elite 9mm
postcontent:
I have for sale or trade, a beautiful 92G Brigadier Elite with both original clips, the Beretta lock, in original box with the manual.  This gun has been fired approx. 150 times, at the range, over the past 10 years or so. This is not an Elite IA or an Elite II but the more difficult to find Brigadier Elite I. I am also including an Unclle Mike's Side Kick Holster (Never Used) and 200 rounds of WInchester White Box Ammo. 

The Brigadier has a 60-gram (2.1 oz) heavier slide and 1 millimeter (0.039 in) wider to improve control when firing multiple shots in quick succession. It also includes removable front and rear sights.

The Elite I Pistols include the heavier Brigadier bruniton slide with front serrations and Elite designation, Inox finish (silver) stainless barrel, thin skeletonized hammer, and bevel of the magazine well. A flat hammer spring cap was standard as well as the decock only (G-Model) feature and dovetailed front sight. 

She is a beauty but I am streamlining my caliber line up and the 9mm's are going.  This is the last 9mm I have remaining and am having a little separation anxiety already.  I am always interested in 45 ACP and AR 15 (.223) trades with cash up or down based on what you have to trade.  Shoot me an offer before I change my mind.  FTF with ID for transaction please.

title: For Trade:  Ruger 50th anniversary flat top blackhawk 44 mag
location: Midtown/edge mere park, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma
postcontent:
I'm looking to trade my ruger 50th anniversary flat top blackhawk 44 mag revolver. This was a limited edition issued in 2006 to commerate 50 years of the 44 mag cartridge.

The ruger blackhawk is notoriously strong to the point that several maximum loads are recommended only for ruger revolvers, this makes them a favorite of hand loaders and hunters.

This revolver has a 6.5" barrel and a steel grip frame (not aluminum like on current production) and features gold roll marking on the barrel.

Being a collectable item it has been fed >250 rounds in its life and has no dings or damage of any kind. There is a slight cylinder draw line, but that is expected for a revolver of this style in a blued finish.

Is was my camping back up for many years, and I'd rather have a shooter, not a collectors piece.

I'm wanting to trade for another 44 mag. I really want a ruger redhawk, but I'd consider a s&w 29, 629 or (maybe) a Taurus raging bull.

or i'd sell for $500.

title: For Sale:  Colt 1911 Gold Cup National Match 1976 MINT!
postcontent:
I recently acquired this Colt 1911 Gold Cup National Match Mark IV Series 70 pistol in a trade and it's so nice that I've decided to sell it.  Typically I like to shoot my 1911's but I'm pretty sure this has not had more than the factory rounds through it, so I feel guilty wearing it in - it feels like it should be preserved and I'm just not that kind of person.  It's in fantastic shape and only has a little wear in the bluing on the front of the slide from being in the box (hard to see in photos because it's so minor.  There is also a tiny nick below the trigger on the trigger guard on the ejection side.  It's small but I have photos to show it.  The serial # puts it at 1976 and the gun is tight and smooth - they just don't make them like this anymore!   I would call this a 99% gun and hopefully the photos show it.  The bore is shiny and appears to he never had any rounds down the tube.  I have several high resolution photos that I can email to anyone in case these photos don't do it justice.

The gun comes with the original styrofoam inside box (not cardboard box) and paperwork from 1976!  It also came with a screwdriver tool and the bushing tool from Colt.  Again, this is truly a piece of history.  Though I would prefer to do a cash transaction, I am open to partial trades for cash and another 1911 that I can shoot and not devalue in the process!! :)

I'm also interested in trades for a Dillon 1050 press or maybe a 50BMG rifle of some sort.

Thanks for looking.  Feel free to email me with any questions.
